x4freetext: REFERENCE Is corrected.
Date is corrected
Otto`S remark is included/
Last checking has been done.
The uranium foils target was of natural isotopic
composition. (99.29% U-238). The foil density varied
between 170 and 230 mg/cm**2 depending on the nature of
the experiment.
Total number of neutrons emitted in the asymmetric
fission of U-238.
A 30-cm**3 Ge(Li) detector and a 40-cm**3 Ge(Li)
detector for gamma-rays.
Gas-flow B- counters.
NaI(Tl) scintillation crystal for monitor.
Stack assembly contains of the uranium foil,
high-purity aluminium catcher foils, a Cu monitor foil.
The duration of the irradiation varied from 2
to 25 minutes.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Journal of Inorganic and Nuclear Chemistry, Vol.35, p.361 (1973)

x4freetext: .The total error was assessed for each nuclide
by taking the square root of the sum of the squares of
individual errors connected with both the nuclide and
the monitor.
Errors were divided into systematic and random.The
systemetic errors are associated with monitor cross
section, detector efficiencies,branching ratios and
half-life values.Errors involved in the cross sections
used in beam monitoring have already been quoted as
+-5.9%. Errors in decay scheme uncertainties varied
between 1 and 12 while isomer branching ratio
uncertainties were 2-3%. Errors in the actual sample
measurements were 1-3%. The energy spread in the
internal circulating beam is on the average +-2 MeV.
Errors in efficiency calibtation of detectors are 2%
for the gamma-ray detectors and 7% for the cross
calibration used for Ag-112. An error of +-3% was
allowed for sample reproducibility.
The random errors are connected with beta and gamma
activity measurements, chemical yields, foil thickness
and alignments. The main source of error lies in the
determination of photopeak areas (5-15%) depending on
the complexity of the gamma-ray spectra. The error in
obtaining the initial disintegration rate varied from
2% [extrapolation of Cu-64 decay curve] to 10% for
specific nuclides. Weighing and pipetting contributed
1.5-2%, 1-3% was contributed by timing in separations.
Chemical yields were determined in duplicate or
triplicate. They agreed within 3-5%. The error in foil
area determination was assessed at 1%.
46% isomer
transition.

x4freetext: The cross section of Pd-111-m could be considered
independent since the decay of the Rh-111 parent is
greater than 99% to the ground state.
B0019001 have reported the isomer ratio of
Pd-111-m/Pd-111-g to be 2.5+-0.6 and to be virtually
identical in low- and high-energy fission and thus the
total cross section could be computed for this nuclide.
